class Solution {
public:
    void setZeroes(vector<vector<int>>& M) {
        int n=  M.size();
        int m=  M[0].size();

        vector<int> row(n,0);
        vector<int> col(m,0);

        //mark rows and columns
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
                if(M[i][j]==0){
                    row[i]=1;
                    col[j]=1;
                }
            }  
        }

        //set zeros
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
                if(row[i]==1 || col[j]==1){
                    M[i][j]=0;
                }
            }
        }
    }
};


--------------------------------


🧠 What are row[] and col[] doing?

👉 They are just markers (flags)
👉 They don’t store values, they just say:

1 = this row/column should become zero
0 = leave it as it is
🔍 Example

Matrix:

1 1 1
1 0 1
1 1 1
🟡 Step 1: Marking

When we find 0 at (1,1):

row[1] = 1;
col[1] = 1;

👉 Means:

Entire row 1 should become 0
Entire column 1 should become 0
🟢 After marking
row = [0, 1, 0]
col = [0, 1, 0]
🔴 Step 2: Apply changes

Now we check:

if(row[i] == 1 || col[j] == 1)
    make M[i][j] = 0;
✅ Final matrix
1 0 1
0 0 0
1 0 1
🧠 Simple understanding

👉

row[i] = 1 → “this row has a zero somewhere”
col[j] = 1 → “this column has a zero somewhere”
🎯 One-line memory trick

👉 “Row/Col array just remembers where zeros were found”
